-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                    THE TEENY-TINY ATARI 2600 DEMO
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                         a tiny Atari 2600 demo

  Released : Thursday, July 16, 2026
  Platform : Atari 2600 / Atari VCS (NTSC)
  Format   : 4096-byte 4K cartridge ROM, no bank switching
  Controls : none - the demo runs automatically and reads no input

  Credits
  -------
  Squeepty .......................... code, visuals, TIA adaptation
  Lloyd Russell ..................... original Jukebox type-in

  Opening sequence
  ----------------
  The one-time first scene reveals one major layer every 256 frames:

    stage 1   SQUEEPTY title
    stage 2   checker/grid
    stage 3   bouncing spaceship and moving starfield
    stage 4   compact scrolling ticker

  Scene two starts when stage four ends. There is no extra 1,024-frame hold
  on the completed first scene.

  Four scenes
  -----------
  1. static title       alien/diamond, classic checks, slow stars
  2. type on and off    robot, digital blocks, medium stars
  3. horizontal ripple  UFO, narrow bands, fast stars
  4. vertical wave      space jellyfish, chunky blocks, reverse stars

  The scene-specific player sprites bounce in both axes. Checker patterns
  animate, sparse star planes move behind the sprites, and regular scene
  changes use a 256-frame luminance fade.

  Sound
  -----
  The 66.75-second, two-channel TIA adaptation of Take On Me is derived from
  Jukebox by Lloyd Russell, published as a type-in in Your Sinclair issue 21,
  September 1987, for the ZX Spectrum 128K. Channel 0 carries the selected AY
  lead voice and channel 1 carries the bass. Compact duration, pitch, waveform
  and volume events update once per NTSC frame, independently of the visual
  scene counter, and loop at the end.

  Also inside
  -----------
  * flowing top, middle and bottom raster bars
  * color-cycling background behind the 40-bit SQUEEPTY playfield title
  * five-row GREETINGS TO ALL ATARI DREAMERS... ticker, stored compactly
  * fixed 262-line NTSC frames: 3 sync, 37 blank, 192 visible, 30 overscan

  Run SQUEEPTY.BIN in Stella or on suitable NTSC Atari 2600 hardware.

  The archive contains the ROM, README, NFO and FILE_ID.DIZ. Source and notes:
  https://github.com/squeepty/2600-demo

  Video capture:
  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SjKJ531LlC0

